hat and that hair.

02:58.012 --> 03:00.846
You're clearly
a man of taste. Step
up here, would you?

03:00.848 --> 03:03.015
Take a look at
this marvelous machine.

03:03.850 --> 03:06.885
Wow! The future's
gonna be amazing!

03:06.887 --> 03:09.888
Flying machines,
household electrification,

03:09.890 --> 03:11.890
steam-powered submarines!

03:11.892 --> 03:15.394
Personally, I'm looking
forward to cheese that
comes in aerosol cans.

03:15.528 --> 03:16.762
Still hard
at work, Dad?

03:16.764 --> 03:19.598
Well, hello there,
my young fellows!

03:19.600 --> 03:23.135
Find anything good yet?
Oh, just some old
Civil War coins.

03:23.137 --> 03:25.804
COIN: <i>The Union</i>
<i>assault against</i>
<i>the sunken road</i>

03:25.806 --> 03:27.504
<i>eventually pierced</i>
<i>the Confederate center,</i>

03:27.506 --> 03:30.108
<i>but the Federal advantage</i>
<i>was not followed...</i>
<i>PHINEAS: Dad?</i>

03:30.143 --> 03:33.045
Dad?
I'm sorry, we've got,
uh, chores to do.

03:33.047 --> 03:35.380
Oh, yes, yes, yes.
Go ahead, boys.

03:35.382 --> 03:36.882
Don't let me
stop you.

03:37.951 --> 03:39.785
COIN: <i>As I was saying...</i>

03:40.453 --> 03:45.424
♪ Oh, I'm a trudging
to get some water down
this old and dusty road

03:45.426 --> 03:48.827
♪ I reckon
there'll be more someday
than just tree sticks and... ♪

03:48.829 --> 03:50.529
Wait a minute!
Wait a minute!

03:50.531 --> 03:51.964
You should be doing
your farm chores.

03:51.966 --> 03:54.466
Milking the cows,
mending the fences,
shucking the corn,

03:54.468 --> 03:56.468
plowing the fields,
and milking
the cows again.

03:56.470 --> 03:57.703
You can't just
stand around, you know?

03:57.705 --> 03:59.738
Actually, Candace,
we were thinking
about a way

03:59.740 --> 04:02.741
to do our chores using
modern steam technology.

04:02.743 --> 04:04.443
We learned all about it
at the World's Fair.

04:04.445 --> 04:07.646
Oh, did you now?
Well, if I didn't
have to haul water,

04:07.648 --> 04:09.781
sweep the barn,
collect eggs,
spin a quilt,

04:09.783 --> 04:12.150
and do whatever
this is, I'd tell Mom.

04:12.152 --> 04:13.852
I wonder if she knows
those buckets
have holes in them?

04:13.854 --> 04:16.021
Hello, boys.
We would like
to inquire as to

04:16.023 --> 04:18.190
what you are doing
at this moment?

04:18.192 --> 04:20.092
Well, like we were
just telling Candace,

04:20.094 --> 04:21.192
we were just
about to create

04:21.194 --> 04:23.795
a steam-powered machine
that would help
with our...

04:23.797 --> 04:26.431
Hey, where's Sweary?
(PERRY SQUAWKING)

04:26.433 --> 04:27.331
Found him!
Found him!

04:27.333 --> 04:30.469
PHINEAS: Oh, there you are,
Sweary the Swan.
(HONKS)

04:30.471 --> 04:32.704
Man, that pet of yours
gives me the creeps!

04:32.706 --> 04:35.707
Oh, come on, Buford.
You know swans
don't do much.

04:35.709 --> 04:37.042
Don't do much?

04:37.044 --> 04:39.511
The beak bite on my butt
begs to differ.

04:40.780 --> 04:42.547
(HONKS)

04:43.650 --> 04:45.183
(WHIRRING)

04:45.185 --> 04:47.819
<i>Good morning, Agent S.</i>
<i>This is Major Megaburns.</i>

04:47.821 --> 04:50.555
<i>Your archenemy,</i>
<i>Professor von Doofenshmirtz,</i>

04:50.557 --> 04:53.925
<i>has been spotted</i>
<i>creating something evil</i>
<i>in his laboratory.</i>

04:53.927 --> 04:54.725
<i>Go check it out.</i>

04:54.727 --> 04:58.830
<i>Perhaps Sweary</i>
<i>would wanna try my</i>
<i>steam-powered jetpack.</i>

04:58.832 --> 05:01.266
<i>It's very heavy and full</i>
<i>of boiling-hot water.</i>

05:01.268 --> 05:03.935
<i>Hey, wait a minute!</i>
<i>How come your</i>
<i>zoetrope image</i>

05:03.937 --> 05:05.704
<i>is so much cooler</i>
<i>than mine?</i>

05:05.706 --> 05:08.106
CARL: <i>It's not cooler, sir,</i>
<i>it's just got more frames.</i>

05:08.841 --> 05:10.042
(HONKING)

05:10.044 --> 05:13.779
CHORUS: <i>♪ Doofenshmirtz</i>
<i>Doofenshmirtz, Doofenshmirtz</i>

05:13.781 --> 05:16.948
<i>♪ Doofenshmirtz</i>
<i>Evil Amalgamated ♪</i>

05:17.150 --> 05:18.583
(RATTLING)

05:18.585 --> 05:21.153
Ah, Sweary the Swan!

05:21.155 --> 05:24.256
How completely
unforeseen is your...

05:24.258 --> 05:26.925
Uh,
hang on a second.

05:26.927 --> 05:28.193
(RATTLING STOPS)

05:28.195 --> 05:30.228
Ah, that's better.
Sweary the Swan!

05:30.230 --> 05:33.699
How completely unforeseen
is your presence here.

05:33.701 --> 05:35.834
And by that, I mean,
completely foreseen!

05:35.836 --> 05:37.269
(QUACKS)
Hey, no bites.

05:37.271 --> 05:38.904
I've got a little
something for you.

05:38.906 --> 05:40.739
Well, hello there!

05:40.741 --> 05:44.876
Allow me to introduce
to you my sidekick,
Pneumatic Pnorman.

05:44.878 --> 05:46.778
And both of those
are spelt with a "P."
You know, the...

05:46.780 --> 05:48.113
The "P's" are silent.

05:48.115 --> 05:49.881
I don't even know
why they put
'em in there

05:49.883 --> 05:51.283
if they're not
gonna pronounce it.

05:51.285 --> 05:53.085
It's just a waste
of a good letter.

05:53.087 --> 05:56.088
That's what it is.
But I babble.
Back on topic...

05:56.090 --> 05:58.724
Shall I put
this cucumber
in the salad, sir?

05:58.726 --> 06:01.226
That's not a cucumber,
Pnorm. I'm sorry
about that, Sweary.

06:01.228 --> 06:03.228
He has problems
identifying objects.

06:03.230 --> 06:06.531
Pnorm, that's a swan,
and we're going to tie him
to the railroad tracks.

06:06.533 --> 06:07.699
How melodramatic!

06:07.701 --> 06:09.134
(HONKING)

06:09.268 --> 06:12.804
Wow! Do you
preen your feathers
with that mouth?

06:12.806 --> 06:14.773
They should call you S...

06:14.775 --> 06:17.042
Oh! Oh, I get it!

06:17.044 --> 06:18.810
Sweary the Swan.

06:18.812 --> 06:21.279
Okay,
we're all set, Ferb.
Start her up.

06:23.983 --> 06:25.550
Shuck the corn!

06:29.722 --> 06:30.822
Milk the cows!

06:31.724 --> 06:32.958
(WHIRRING)

06:34.127 --> 06:36.661
(CLANKING)
Mend the fences!

06:42.301 --> 06:44.936
And lastly,
plow and seed
the field.

06:47.340 --> 06:49.674
I feel like I've been
carrying these buckets
all summer!

06:49.676 --> 06:51.843
I'll never get to the fair
in time to meet Jeremy!

06:51.845 --> 06:52.943
(STEAM WHISTLE BLOWING)

06:52.945 --> 06:56.915
PHINEAS: Hey, Candace!
Is that a steam-powered
chore-doing device?

06:57.017 --> 06:58.817
You are so
going to get it!

06:58.819 --> 07:00.952
Get back here,
you steam punks!

07:00.954 --> 07:03.855
Sorry, Candace,
it won't stop
till we run out of coal!

07:03.857 --> 07:06.892
I shall go fetch Mother!
Ma!

07:06.894 --> 07:09.795
Sweary the Swan, did you
know that the World's Fair
is in town?

07:09.996 --> 07:13.265
They have all of this
amazing new technology.
Here, look.

07:13.267 --> 07:15.767
It's all represented here
on this commemorative coin
that I got.

07:15.769 --> 07:17.736
Ow! Now, look
what you did.

07:17.738 --> 07:18.770
You made me drop it.

07:18.772 --> 07:20.839
Pnorman,
go find that coin.

07:20.841 --> 07:22.841
It's probably
right at your feet, sir.

07:22.843 --> 07:26.044
I can't bend over
without pulling my axles
out of alignment.

07:26.046 --> 07:27.913
Yeah, whatever,
think of something.

07:27.915 --> 07:30.916
Anyway,
like I was saying before
you bit my thumb,

07:30.918 --> 07:32.416
down at the fair
they have all these

07:32.418 --> 07:35.954
neat, new steam-powered
gizmos that they plan
to use for progress.

07:35.956 --> 07:37.454
Normally, I wouldn't
mind, but they're

07:37.456 --> 07:40.759
also attaching a lot
of hope and optimism
to progress,

07:40.761 --> 07:42.828
and that's something
I will not put up with.

07:42.830 --> 07:48.333
So, I've built a big
monster machine to smash
their World's Fair to bits!

07:48.734 --> 07:52.204
Behold! It's
an evil swan! It's a...

07:52.206 --> 07:54.105
It's a big swan.
It's like you, but,

07:54.107 --> 07:56.975
you know, bigger
and hammer-ier.

07:56.977 --> 07:58.944
It's got more hammers
than you do.

08:01.481 --> 08:05.684
Plus, it runs on
the new technology of steam!

08:05.918 --> 08:08.086
Sir, I found your coin.

08:08.088 --> 08:10.889
That's not a coin.
That's my daughter,
you dolt!

08:10.891 --> 08:12.791
No wonder
she wouldn't fit
in the gumball machine.

08:12.793 --> 08:13.892
(STEAM WHISTLE BLOWING)

08:13.894 --> 08:15.427
You hear that,
Sweary the Swan?

08:15.429 --> 08:17.963
That is the sound of...
(WHISTLE BLOWING LOUDLY)

08:19.131 --> 08:20.832
Aerosol cheese!

08:22.335 --> 08:24.803
We didn't hear
what you said!

08:24.805 --> 08:26.438
Oh, for...
(WHISTLE BLOWING LOUDLY)

08:26.440 --> 08:28.974
CANDACE: Ma!
Oh, these new gadgets
are so complicated.

08:28.976 --> 08:31.877
Up and down, and up
and down and up...
Ma!

08:31.879 --> 08:33.345
Ma! Ma! The boys!

08:33.347 --> 08:35.947
Machine to do
their chores!
Not fair!

08:35.949 --> 08:37.749
Oh, my!
That sounds exciting.

08:37.751 --> 08:41.386
I'll come have a look
as soon as I'm done
doing whatever this is.

08:41.787 --> 08:44.923
I don't believe it!
A fuzzy doll in
the shape of a bear?

08:44.925 --> 08:46.925
It's the end of decency.

08:46.927 --> 08:49.928
You never believed in me
or anthropomorphism.

08:50.196 --> 08:51.897
(PEOPLE SCREAMING)

08:52.765 --> 08:56.268
MAN: Everybody, run!
It's a big hammery swan!

08:56.270 --> 09:00.972
Ha! Soon you will all see
the power of my...
(WHISTLE BLOWING LOUDLY)

09:00.974 --> 09:02.440
(INAUDIBLE)

09:02.442 --> 09:04.109
We can't hear you!

09:04.111 --> 09:05.744
(WHISTLE BLOWING)

09:05.746 --> 09:07.178
(HONKING)

09:07.180 --> 09:09.147
(WHIRRING)

09:23.863 --> 09:25.430
(PEOPLE SCREAMING)

09:29.802 --> 09:33.204
Look! A huge, rampaging,
steam-powered hammery swan!

09:33.206 --> 09:35.740
If only there was
a way we could
record this event.

09:35.742 --> 09:39.110
Auguste, you have just
invented the moving
picture documentary.

09:39.112 --> 09:40.779
Quickly, mood music!

09:40.781 --> 09:41.913
(RAGTIME PIANO PLAYING)

09:45.918 --> 09:47.118
(INAUDIBLE)

10:06.839 --> 10:08.840
This sure is a lot
of shucked corn
and fresh milk.

10:08.842 --> 10:10.775
All in
an afternoon's work.

10:10.777 --> 10:13.878
Aren't you a bit young
to be industrial
revolutionaries?

10:13.880 --> 10:15.513
Yes. Yes, we are.

10:15.515 --> 10:18.316
As a simple farmer
from a bygone age,

10:18.318 --> 10:19.416
that's good enough
for me.

10:19.418 --> 10:22.487
All right, Spartacus,
let's get these goods
to market,

10:22.489 --> 10:24.556
and then it's back to
the bookcase for you.

10:24.558 --> 10:25.256
(NEIGHING)

10:25.258 --> 10:28.927
All our chores
are done and it's
still light out.

10:28.929 --> 10:30.362
What else do you guys
wanna do today?

10:30.364 --> 10:32.364
We could drink lemonade
and sit on the porch.

10:32.366 --> 10:34.532
We could go to Panama
and start digging.

10:34.534 --> 10:36.334
We could formally
begin courting.
What?

10:36.336 --> 10:37.869
Nothing.

10:38.904 --> 10:40.205
(SCREECHING)

10:44.577 --> 10:47.278
They built
a giant machine that
does their chores.

10:47.280 --> 10:50.181
It shucks the corn,
and it shoots seeds
out of a Gatling gu...

10:51.017 --> 10:53.385
But, but, but...
Candace,
it's 1903.

10:53.387 --> 10:54.953
We do not use that word!

10:55.354 --> 10:56.988
No, no, no, you're not
getting my best side.

10:56.990 --> 10:59.858
But here, let me
show you my worst side!

11:03.262 --> 11:06.164
What? Sweary the Swan!
(HONKING)

11:06.432 --> 11:07.966
Ah, you wanna play
swan-chicken, huh?

11:11.404 --> 11:12.937
Oh, no. Get back here!

11:18.244 --> 11:21.012
Oh, no!
He's using the old
foie gras maneuver.

11:21.014 --> 11:22.914
(DOOFENSHMIRTZ SCREAMING)

11:23.916 --> 11:26.451
Curse you,
Sweary the Swan!

11:27.953 --> 11:30.388
DAD: <i>And that's</i>
<i>the way it was at</i>
<i>the Danville World's Fair.</i>

11:30.390 --> 11:33.124
A giant steam-powered
hammering swan?

11:33.126 --> 11:35.326
Come on, Dad.
That sounds
a little far-fetched

11:35.328 --> 11:36.561
for the time period,
doesn't it?

11:36.563 --> 11:38.630
Oh, yes.
